D. Galkovsky's quote about secret societies ("If an organization was founded 300 years ago, that's quite likely. If it's 2,000 years old, remove a zero. If it claims to be 10 000 years old, check last week's newspapers.") also applies to anything related to biology and nutrition.

If some drug has been used since the early 20th century or a bit earlier, it's probably pretty trustworthy and safe overall. If it's a Tibetan mountain herbal dirt extract used for 2000 years by centenarian local peasants, it's probably an 80s New Age supplement for Californians.

And if something has been an important factor for early human evolution from monkeys and was practiced in pre-history by all Neanderthal hunter-gatherers who hunted down mammoths with spears or whatever, it's most likely a scam invented in 2010 or a late 20th industrial byproduct

Dr. Ray Peat says: "Going to sleep and the few minutes after waking up are good times to see how things are working.", which is interesting if you keep in mind Baron Evola also points out the minutes falling asleep (and waking up) as an important time for spiritual introspection.

This is from the same email Dr. Peat mentions there are 16 intestinal cycles through the day. He names Frank A. Brown Jr., Solco Tromp, and Michel Gauquelin as researchers who tried to study various biorhythms like the nasal cycles. Probably good idea to look into their work too.
For the average person, this comes down to: If you feel a random urge to nap through the day, it's good to follow through with it.
